+# ts-edge Assessment For Pibo Workflow MVP
+
+## 1. Metadata
+
+- Project: ts-edge
+- Local source: `/root/code/ts-edge`
+- Key evidence read: `/root/code/ts-edge/README.md`, `/root/code/ts-edge/package.json`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/registry.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/runable.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/node-executor.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/store.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/core.test.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/state-graph.test.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/complex-case.test.ts`
+- License observed locally: MIT (`/root/code/ts-edge/package.json`, `/root/code/ts-edge/LICENSE`)
+- Version observed locally: `1.0.4` (`/root/code/ts-edge/package.json`)
+- Assessment date: 2026-05-07
+- Pibo reference context: `/root/code/pibo/GLOSSARY.md`, `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`, `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-product-projects-area.md`, `/root/code/pibo/docs/projects/workflow-framework-research-plan.md`, `/root/code/pibo/docs/projects/workflow-framework-first-assessment-2026-05-07.md`
+
+## 2. One-line Verdict
+
+ts-edge is a strong **reference** for a small typed graph workflow API, especially around typed node connections, execution events, and conditional routing, but it is not yet a close enough match to Pibo’s workflow-run, tracing, persistence, and session-orchestration needs to adopt directly as the core engine.
+
+## 3. What Problem It Solves
+
+ts-edge solves a narrow and useful problem: building lightweight graph-based execution pipelines in TypeScript with compile-time checking of node-to-node compatibility. The library is centered on a fluent graph builder, typed nodes, typed edges, dynamic routing, merge nodes for parallel branches, and a runnable execution object. The README and interfaces show two primary modes: a dataflow graph and a shared-state graph (`/root/code/ts-edge/README.md`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/registry.ts`).
+
+For Pibo, that means ts-edge is not a “workflow product model” by itself. It is closer to a minimal in-memory graph execution kernel. It does not try to own sessions, user feedback phases, project/worktree lifecycle, durable workflow runs, or product-level actor identities. That narrower scope is attractive for MVP inspiration because Pibo explicitly wants a small Workflow layer rather than a heavy framework (`/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`, `/root/code/pibo/docs/projects/workflow-framework-research-plan.md`).
+
+## 4. Core Abstractions Observed
+
+1. **Typed graph nodes**: `GraphNode` carries `name`, `input`, `output`, and optional `metadata` (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`).
+2. **Compile-time connectability**: `ConnectableNode`, `InputOf`, and `OutputOf` enforce edge compatibility in the builder API (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`). This is the strongest directly relevant idea for Pibo’s typed workflow graph API.
+3. **Graph registries**: `createGraph()` and `createStateGraph()` build immutable-looking fluent registries that later compile into runnable graphs (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/registry.ts`).
+4. **Direct edges and dynamic edges**: static routing via `.edge(...)`; conditional routing via `.dynamicEdge(...)`, including declared `possibleTargets` for documentation/visualization (`/root/code/ts-edge/README.md`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`).
+5. **Merge nodes**: explicit fan-in after parallel branches, with source branch names declared on the merge node (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/runable.ts`).
+6. **Execution events**: workflow start/end, node start/end, and node stream events, all emitted through subscription (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/core.test.ts`).
+7. **Shared-state graph store**: `graphStore` plus `createStateGraph()` provide a mutable shared state model rather than pure output-to-input passing (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/store.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/registry.ts`).
+8. **Middleware and exit control**: runnable graphs can intercept node execution, rewrite routing, or stop execution (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/runable.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/core.test.ts`).
+
+## 5. Fit Against Pibo Requirements
+
+| Requirement area | ts-edge fit | Evidence | Notes for Pibo |
+| --- | --- | --- | --- |
+| Lightweight TS workflow core | Strong | `/root/code/ts-edge/README.md`, `/root/code/ts-edge/package.json` | Matches Pibo’s MVP preference for a small native layer. |
+| Typed graph workflow API | Strong | `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts` | Best part of the library for Pibo to study closely. |
+| Node/edge typing | Strong | `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts` | Compile-time connectability is better than many ad hoc graph designs. |
+| Conditional routing | Strong | `/root/code/ts-edge/README.md`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/core.test.ts` | Dynamic edges map well to workflow transitions and loop decisions. |
+| Parallel branches and fan-in | Strong | `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/runable.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/core.test.ts` | Useful for future multi-runtime or multi-agent branches. |
+| Execution events / tracing hooks | Medium-Strong | `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/node-executor.ts` | Good start, but below Pibo’s required workflow trace richness. |
+| Explicit workflow state machine semantics | Medium | `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/store.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/test/state-graph.test.ts` | Shared mutable state exists, but state transitions are not first-class. |
+| Pibo Session / Workflow Run association | Weak | No matching product abstraction observed in `/root/code/ts-edge/src/*` | Would need a Pibo-owned wrapper or replacement layer. |
+| User/agent initiator identity | Weak | Event shapes in `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts` lack actor identity | Pibo requires initiator and nested workflow context. |
+| Durable persistence / resumability | Weak | No persistence layer observed in `/root/code/ts-edge/src/*` | Major gap for Pibo’s long-lived workflow direction. |
+| Retry/failure policy semantics | Weak-Medium | Timeout/max visits in `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts`, `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/runable.ts` | Has execution guards, but not workflow-level retry semantics. |
+| Project/session/worktree/worker orchestration | Weak | No such abstractions observed | Pibo must own this completely. |
+| Agent-callable workflow boundary | Weak | No usage-mode concept observed | Pibo needs `session-only`, `agent-only`, `session-and-agent`. |
+| Product-level graph trace explainability | Medium | Histories/events in `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts` | Node execution trace exists, but transition reasons and dataflow semantics are shallow. |
+
+## 6. Useful Concepts For Pibo
+
+The most useful concept is the **typed connectability model**. Pibo wants graph nodes and edges without adopting a giant framework. ts-edge shows one credible way to model node names, node input/output types, and route legality using TypeScript type utilities rather than runtime schema registration.
+
+The second useful concept is the split between **builder time** and **runtime**. `createGraph()` assembles a graph definition, then `compile()` produces a runnable executor (`/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/registry.ts`). Pibo could use the same shape while attaching product metadata, workflow usage mode, and trace policies.
+
+The third useful concept is **dynamic routing with declared possible targets**. That is valuable for Pibo because workflow traces and UI graph inspection need more than “router function exists”; they need a predictable list of possible transitions.
+
+The fourth useful concept is the **event subscription surface**. ts-edge already emits start/end and stream events. Pibo can extend that idea into durable `WorkflowTraceEvent` records with richer payloads, rather than inventing the whole event vocabulary from zero.
+
+Finally, **merge nodes** are relevant. Pibo’s V1 Standard Project Workflow is mostly linear, but future project, research, and subagent workflows will need fan-out/fan-in patterns.
+
+## 7. Mismatches And Risks
+
+The biggest mismatch is that ts-edge is an **execution library**, while Pibo needs a **product workflow model**. Pibo Workflows must own state, transitions, traces, usage restrictions, and links to Sessions and Projects (`/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`, `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-product-projects-area.md`). ts-edge does not cover that boundary.
+
+Second, ts-edge’s “state graph” is shared mutable state, not a first-class state machine. Pibo needs visible workflow states like `spec`, `implementation`, `test`, `user_feedback`, `completed`, `failed`, and `discarded`, plus explicit transition records. ts-edge can implement loops, but it does not naturally explain them as workflow state changes.
+
+Third, durability is absent. There is no observed persisted workflow-run store, checkpoint system, or resume semantics. For Pibo, that means any direct adoption would quickly force a large wrapper around the library, reducing the value of adopting it at all.
+
+Fourth, execution events are useful but not enough. Pibo needs actor identity, run ids, parent workflow context, transition reasons, runtime/session/worktree/worker starts, user feedback actions, and cleanup actions. ts-edge’s events are closer to low-level runtime telemetry.
+
+Fifth, the project appears relatively small. The tests are helpful and reasonably broad, but the ecosystem maturity and long-term maintenance confidence look lower than larger references such as XState or LangGraph.js.
+
+## 8. Minimal Pibo-Native Borrowing Candidates
+
+1. **Typed node definition pattern**: a Pibo `WorkflowNodeDefinition<Name, In, Out>` inspired by ts-edge’s node typing.
+2. **Typed edge legality utilities**: adapt the idea behind `ConnectableNode`, `InputOf`, and `OutputOf` into Pibo-owned types.
+3. **Dynamic edge API**: keep a `router` plus optional `possibleTargets` declaration.
+4. **Merge/fan-in node concept**: useful for future parallel branches and subworkflow joins.
+5. **Execution event vocabulary shape**: reuse the basic idea of node start/end/stream hooks, but convert them into Pibo workflow trace events.
+6. **Compile-to-runnable split**: definition first, compiled run plan second.
+
+These are good cleanroom borrowing targets because they are conceptual API ideas, not reasons to transplant implementation code.
+
+## 9. Open Questions / Follow-up Files
+
+- How much of ts-edge’s compile-time type model survives once Pibo adds workflow state classes and session/runtime node kinds? Inspect `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts` more deeply.
+- Does ts-edge’s parallel scheduling model have corner cases around duplicate merge activation or branch cancellation? Inspect `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/runable.ts` and `/root/code/ts-edge/src/core/thread-pool.ts`.
+- Would Pibo prefer explicit transition objects over router functions? Compare `/root/code/ts-edge/src/interfaces.ts` with `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`.
+- Can Pibo express `standard-project` cleanly as a typed graph plus explicit state transitions, or should graph and state machine stay partly separate? Re-check `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-product-projects-area.md`.
+- Which trace events should be first-class in Pibo MVP beyond ts-edge’s event model? Re-check `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md` and the `WorkflowTraceEvent` draft in `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-product-projects-area.md`.
+
+## 10. Recommendation
+
+Recommendation: **use ts-edge as a high-value reference only, not as a direct core dependency for Pibo Workflow MVP**.
+
+Why: it is one of the best local references for the exact narrow area Pibo needs right now—typed graph API, node/edge typing, conditional routing, merge behavior, and execution events. But it is still too low-level and too in-memory for Pibo’s actual workflow product boundary. Pibo should study it closely, then implement a small Pibo-native Workflow API that preserves the good parts while adding Pibo-specific concepts: workflow usage modes, workflow runs, explicit state transitions, durable traces, session/project linkage, user feedback nodes, and runtime/worktree/worker orchestration.
+
+In short: **borrow the API ideas, not the engine wholesale**.
