+# XState Assessment For Pibo Workflow MVP
+
+## 1. Metadata
+
+- Candidate: XState
+- Local repo studied: `/root/code/xstate`
+- Version observed: `5.31.0` in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/package.json`
+- License observed: MIT in `/root/code/xstate/LICENSE`
+- Assessment date: 2026-05-07
+- Pibo reference files read:
+  - `/root/code/pibo/GLOSSARY.md`
+  - `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`
+  - `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-product-projects-area.md`
+  - `/root/code/pibo/docs/projects/workflow-framework-research-plan.md`
+  - `/root/code/pibo/docs/projects/workflow-framework-first-assessment-2026-05-07.md`
+
+## 2. One-line Verdict
+
+Strong reference for workflow state semantics and actor orchestration, but not a clean direct fit as Pibo’s core workflow engine.
+
+## 3. What Problem It Solves
+
+XState solves explicit, event-driven control flow for complex logic. Its center of gravity is: define machine states, transitions, guards, actions, invoked async work, and actor relationships; then run that logic predictably through actor instances. The repo presents it as “Actor-based state management & orchestration for complex app logic” in `/root/code/xstate/README.md`, and the examples show that this extends beyond UI widgets into backend-style workflows such as `/root/code/xstate/examples/express-workflow/index.ts`, `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-book-lending/main.ts`, and `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-async-subflow/main.ts`.
+
+For Pibo, that matters because the workflow spec says the Workflow owns state machine, graph, orchestration, and tracing, while Sessions remain run/interaction contexts (`/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`). XState is good at the “explicit behavior and transitions” part of that requirement.
+
+## 4. Core Abstractions Observed
+
+- **Statecharts / machines**: `createMachine(...)` and `setup(...).createMachine(...)` are the main definition forms. Examples show hierarchical, parallel, history, final, always, after, and event-driven states in `/root/code/xstate/README.md` and `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-book-lending/main.ts`.
+- **Actors**: machine logic becomes a running actor with `createActor(...)`. Child actors and invoked actors are first-class. See `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-async-subflow/main.ts`.
+- **Events**: transitions are driven by typed events (`on`, `always`, `after`, `onDone`, `onError`).
+- **Guards**: conditional routing is explicit, e.g. `guard: 'isOver18'` in `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-applicant-request/main.ts`.
+- **Actions**: transition-time side effects and context updates, commonly via `assign(...)`.
+- **Invocations**: async work is modeled via `invoke` with `fromPromise(...)`, including subworkflow-style invocation.
+- **Snapshots**: running actors expose current snapshots and persisted snapshots via `getSnapshot()` and `getPersistedSnapshot()`; restore happens through `createActor(..., { snapshot })` per `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/types.ts` and `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/createActor.ts`.
+- **Graph utilities**: the core package includes graph traversal/export helpers in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/graph/graph.ts`, including `toDirectedGraph(...)`, but these operate on machine structure rather than defining a separate workflow graph runtime.
+- **Inspection / visualization**: local inspect hooks exist in core, and browser visual tooling exists in `/root/code/xstate/packages/xstate-inspect/README.md`.
+
+## 5. Fit Against Pibo Requirements
+
+| Requirement | Fit | Evidence | Pibo implication |
+| --- | --- | --- | --- |
+| Workflow definition | Medium-High | Typed machine definitions in `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-applicant-request/main.ts` and `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-book-lending/main.ts` | Good for defining workflow behavior explicitly, but Pibo would still need its own `WorkflowDefinition` registry and usage metadata. |
+| Workflow run state | High | `createActor(...)`, `getSnapshot()`, `subscribe(...)` in `/root/code/xstate/README.md` and examples | Strong fit for in-memory run execution. A Workflow Run could map naturally to one root actor. |
+| graph nodes/edges | Medium | `toDirectedGraph(...)` and graph helpers in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/graph/graph.ts` | Usable for visualization/export, but XState’s native model is a statechart tree plus transitions, not Pibo’s broader node/edge runtime abstraction. |
+| transitions/guards | High | Guarded transitions in `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-applicant-request/main.ts`; `always`, `after`, `onDone`, `onError` in `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-book-lending/main.ts` | Excellent semantic reference for explicit transition logic and bounded loop decisions. |
+| tracing/observability | Medium-High | `inspect` option and event types documented in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/types.ts`; inspector package in `/root/code/xstate/packages/xstate-inspect/README.md` | Strong source for machine/actor/event tracing, but Pibo still needs richer workflow-level trace events tied to Sessions, Projects, workers, and user actions. |
+| persistence/resume | Medium-High | `snapshot` restore semantics in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/types.ts`; `getPersistedSnapshot()` in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/createActor.ts`; express persistence example in `/root/code/xstate/examples/express-workflow/index.ts` | Useful for resumable workflow runs. But persistence shape is actor-internal and schema migration remains Pibo’s responsibility. |
+| runtime/session integration | Medium | Async service invocation in examples; actor nesting in `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-async-subflow/main.ts` | Can wrap Pi or PyHosted runtime calls as invoked actors, but XState does not understand Pibo Sessions, child session hierarchy, worktrees, or Docker workers. |
+| agent-callable safety | Medium-Low | XState provides machine mechanics, not policy boundaries | Pibo must own usage modes (`session-only`, `agent-only`, `session-and-agent`) and safe tool surfaces itself, per `/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md`. |
+| TypeScript type safety | High | `setup({ types, actors, guards })` usage in `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-applicant-request/main.ts`; TS-first packaging in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/package.json` | Strong candidate for influencing Pibo’s typed workflow API shape. |
+
+## 6. Useful Concepts For Pibo
+
+1. **State as a first-class contract**: XState makes allowed states and transitions explicit. That aligns directly with Pibo’s requirement that the state machine lives on the Workflow, not on the Session.
+2. **Actor-per-run mental model**: a Workflow Run as one root actor is a clean mapping for MVP execution.
+3. **Invoked async steps**: `invoke` plus `fromPromise(...)` is a useful conceptual model for runtime nodes, user-wait nodes, and subworkflow calls.
+4. **Guards over implicit branching**: Pibo’s loop and retry semantics would benefit from explicit guard functions rather than ad hoc `if` chains.
+5. **Parallel and nested states**: relevant for future multi-runtime or organization-like workflows; shown in `/root/code/xstate/README.md` and `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-parallel/main.ts`.
+6. **Persisted snapshots**: practical baseline for pause/resume behavior in a local-first system.
+7. **Inspectable microsteps and snapshots**: useful reference for designing Pibo Workflow Trace events with state-before/state-after and transition evidence.
+
+## 7. Mismatches And Risks
+
+- **Not a Pibo-native workflow model**: XState is a general statechart/actor runtime. Pibo needs Workflow definitions, Workflow Runs, Session associations, Project semantics, workflow usage modes, and worker/worktree metadata (`/root/code/pibo/spec/projects/spec-product-projects-area.md`).
+- **Statechart-first, not node-runtime-first**: some Pibo workflows may be clearer as graph nodes with dataflow and runtime ownership rather than pure statechart nesting.
+- **Persistence is useful but not sufficient**: XState can restore persisted snapshots, but Pibo still needs durable storage schema, versioning, migration rules, and trace persistence. XState itself warns compatibility is on the application when schemas change; this is implied by restore semantics and historical changelog notes in `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/CHANGELOG.md`.
+- **Actions are ephemeral**: XState intentionally treats actions as side effects, not durable state. That is correct design, but Pibo must separately persist durable trace/output records.
+- **Some child actor persistence limits**: `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/State.ts` throws for inline child actors during persistence. That means Pibo would need disciplined referenced actor definitions if it leaned on deep persistence heavily.
+- **Visualization tooling is external-product-shaped**: Stately tooling is attractive, but Pibo should not couple core workflow understanding to external SaaS/editor assumptions.
+
+## 8. Minimal Pibo-Native Borrowing Candidates
+
+- A typed machine-like workflow DSL: `states`, `on`, `guard`, `actions`, `invoke`.
+- Root-run plus child-actor mental model for subworkflows and delegated runtime calls.
+- Persisted snapshot concept for local resume.
+- Inspection event taxonomy as inspiration: actor created, event sent, snapshot emitted, action executed.
+- Parallel and history semantics only if a concrete Pibo workflow needs them.
+
+## 9. Open Questions / Follow-up Files
+
+- Compare XState’s statechart model against `ts-edge` for graph-native workflow ergonomics.
+- Inspect whether Pibo’s Standard Project Workflow is clearer as one machine or as node graph plus machine state overlay.
+- Decide whether Pibo needs deep child persistence or only root-run checkpoint persistence.
+- Draft Pibo-owned trace event mapping using ideas from `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/types.ts` inspect events.
+- Follow-up files:
+  - `/root/code/xstate/examples/express-workflow/index.ts`
+  - `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-book-lending/main.ts`
+  - `/root/code/xstate/examples/workflow-async-subflow/main.ts`
+  - `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/graph/graph.ts`
+  - `/root/code/xstate/packages/core/src/State.ts`
+
+## 10. Recommendation
+
+Use XState as a **deep semantic reference**, not as the first core dependency for Pibo Workflow MVP.
+
+Reason: it fits Pibo very well at the level of explicit states, transitions, guards, invoked work, actor composition, persisted snapshots, and inspectable runtime behavior. But it does **not** directly provide Pibo’s required product model: Workflow registry, Workflow usage policy, Workflow Trace schema, Session/Project/worktree/worker integration, or a clean node/edge runtime abstraction. The best move is to borrow its vocabulary and some API instincts while building a small Pibo-native workflow layer centered on `Workflow`, `WorkflowRun`, `WorkflowNode`, `WorkflowTransition`, and `WorkflowTrace` as defined in the Pibo specs.
