+---
+title: Pibo Workflow Engine Architecture
+version: 0.1
+date_created: 2026-05-07
+last_updated: 2026-05-07
+owner: Pibo
+status: draft
+tags: [architecture, workflows, state-machine, graph, runtime, sessions, agents, tracing]
+---
+
+# Introduction
+
+This specification defines the target architecture for **Workflows** as Pibo's central process, state, graph, and execution abstraction.
+
+The current product uses Pibo Sessions as the main visible unit of interaction. The target model keeps sessions as interaction and runtime contexts, but moves process logic into Workflows.
+
+The core shift is:
+
+```text
+Workflow = State Machine = Graph = Runtime Model = Process Model = Extensible Execution Unit
+```
+
+A Session may run inside a Workflow. An Agent may call a Workflow as a tool. A Project may contain many Workflow-backed sessions. The Workflow is the unit that owns process logic, state transitions, graph execution, orchestration, and workflow-level tracing.
+
+## 1. Purpose & Scope
+
+This specification covers:
+
+- Workflow as the central execution abstraction.
+- Relationship between Rooms, Projects, Personal Chat, Sessions, Agents, and Workflows.
+- Minimal workflows that preserve current session behavior.
+- Complex workflows that orchestrate multiple runtimes and graph nodes.
+- Workflow usage modes for session and agent contexts.
+- Workflow graph/state-machine architecture.
+- Workflow tracing requirements.
+- Dependency and framework evaluation principles.
+
+Out of scope for this specification:
+
+- Final database schema.
+- Complete UI design.
+- Full implementation of a durable workflow engine.
+- Selecting or approving any external framework dependency.
+
+## 2. Core Model
+
+### 2.1 Product Concept Mapping
+
+The target product model is:
+
+```text
+Rooms = Projects or user-facing containers
+Personal Chat = Standard personal chat room
+Sessions = concrete interaction or run contexts inside a Workflow
+Workflow = central logic, state, graph, and execution unit
+```
+
+A Room is no longer the primary logic container. A Session is no longer the primary process model. The Workflow owns process behavior.
+
+### 2.2 Everything With Process Logic Is A Workflow
+
+Any feature that needs process control, state, dataflow, runtime orchestration, or agent orchestration should be modeled as a Workflow.
+
+Examples:
+
+- Minimal personal chat run.
+- Standard project coding workflow.
+- Research workflow.
+- Cleanup workflow.
+- Agent-internal workflow tool.
+- Multi-runtime project workflow.
+- Future organization-like agent graph.
+
+### 2.3 State Machine Lives On The Workflow
+
+The state machine belongs to the Workflow, not directly to:
+
+- a Room,
+- a Project,
+- a Session,
+- an Agent,
+- a Runtime.
+
+A Session can be associated with a Workflow run, but the Workflow determines valid states, transitions, node execution, available actions, and process logic.
+
+## 3. Workflow Forms
+
+### 3.1 Minimal Workflow
+
+The smallest Workflow form is a simple process run.
+
+It corresponds to today's basic personal chat/session behavior:
+
+```text
+Minimal Workflow
+= one simple run
+= one runtime
+= no explicit agents
+= no subagents
+= no spawning
+= no complex graph
+= current personal chat/session behavior mapped into Workflow architecture
+```
+
+The minimal Workflow is not a temporary compatibility hack. It is the smallest stable cell of the system.
+
+### 3.2 Complex Graph Workflow
+
+A complex Workflow may be a graph that orchestrates multiple nodes, runtimes, and handoffs.
+
+Example:
+
+```text
+Workflow
+→ Node A: Spec
+→ Node B: Implementation
+→ Node C: PyHosted Runtime 1
+→ Node D: Test Runtime
+→ Node E: Review
+→ Node F: User Feedback
+→ Node G: System Update
+```
+
+A complex Workflow can represent an organization-like agent system:
+
+```text
+Workflow as Organization
+= graph
+= multiple nodes
+= multiple runtimes
+= multiple roles
+= multiple handoffs
+= own rules
+= own state
+```
+
+PyHosted runtimes may be started, connected, evaluated, and stopped according to Workflow-defined rules.
+
+## 4. Relationship To Sessions
+
+### 4.1 Sessions As Interaction And Run Contexts
+
+A Session is an interaction or run context for a Workflow.
+
+```text
+Session → Workflow Run
+```
+
+The Session may provide:
+
+- user-visible conversation surface,
+- runtime transcript container,
+- route identity,
+- hierarchy for subagent traces,
+- worktree/Docker worker association,
+- selected profile/runtime context.
+
+The Workflow provides:
+
+- process logic,
+- state machine,
+- graph nodes,
+- transitions,
+- dataflow,
+- orchestration,
+- workflow-level tracing.
+
+### 4.2 Personal Chat Example
+
+```text
+Personal Chat Session
+→ Minimal Workflow
+→ simple runtime run
+```
+
+This preserves current personal chat behavior while aligning it with the Workflow model.
+
+### 4.3 Project Example
+
+```text
+Project Session
+→ Standard Project Workflow
+→ Spec
+→ Implementation
+→ Execution
+→ Test
+→ Loop
+→ User Feedback
+→ System Update
+```
+
+The Session is the visible interaction context. The Workflow is the lifecycle logic.
+
+## 5. Workflows As Agent Tools
+
+Agents must be able to start Workflows through a general workflow tool.
+
+Conceptual tool shape:
+
+```text
+start_workflow(workflow_id, input, context)
+call_workflow(workflow_id, input, context)
+```
+
+This means Workflows can be used from two directions:
+
+```text
+User starts Session Workflow
+Agent starts Workflow as Tool
+```
+
+The same Workflow registry can serve both use cases, subject to usage restrictions.
+
+## 6. Workflow Usage Modes
+
+Not every Workflow is available in every context.
+
+Each Workflow must declare a usage mode:
+
+```ts
+export type WorkflowUsage =
+  | "session-only"
+  | "agent-only"
+  | "session-and-agent";
+```
+
+Usage meanings:
+
+- `session-only`: The Workflow may only be started directly as a user/session workflow.
+- `agent-only`: The Workflow may only be started by agents as an internal tool.
+- `session-and-agent`: The Workflow may be started both by user sessions and by agents.
+
+This creates a controlled shared Workflow pool:
+
+```text
+Session Workflows       Shared Workflows       Agent Workflows
+       |                       |                      |
+ User Sessions       both contexts usable       Agent Calls
+```
+
+## 7. Workflow Interface Draft
+
+The initial API should remain small. Pibo should not copy a large workflow framework prematurely.
+
+Conceptual interface:
+
+```ts
+export type WorkflowUsage =
+  | "session-only"
+  | "agent-only"
+  | "session-and-agent";
+
+export interface Workflow<Input = unknown, State = unknown, Output = unknown> {
+  id: string;
+  name: string;
+  usage: WorkflowUsage;
+
+  run(input: Input, context: WorkflowContext): Promise<WorkflowResult<Output>>;
+  getState(runId: string): Promise<State>;
+}
+
+export interface WorkflowGraph<State = unknown> {
+  nodes: WorkflowNode<State>[];
+  edges: WorkflowEdge<State>[];
+}
+```
+
+The exact TypeScript API may change during implementation. The architectural requirement is that Workflow remains the closed unit for:
+
+- logic control,
+- dataflow,
+- state machine,
+- runtime orchestration,
+- traceability.
+
+## 8. Standard Project Workflow
+
+The standard project workflow remains the default process logic for project implementation work:
+
+```text
+User Input
+→ Spec Creation or Spec Update
+→ Implementation
+→ Execution
+→ Test / Validation
+→ Error or Improvement Loop
+→ User Feedback
+→ System Update / Persistence
+```
+
+Short form:
+
+```text
+Spec → Implementation → Execution → Test → Loop → User Feedback → System Update
+```
+
+This Workflow can run as a session workflow. Later, it may also be callable by agents or other workflows if its usage mode allows it.
+
+## 9. Workflow Tracing
+
+Workflow architecture requires strong tracing at two levels:
+
+1. Existing runtime tracing and terminal views.
+2. New workflow/graph tracing.
+
+Runtime tracing continues to show what individual Pi Coding Agent or PyHosted runtimes did.
+
+Workflow tracing must show:
+
+- which node ran,
+- node input,
+- node output,
+- state before execution,
+- state after execution,
+- transition taken,
+- data passed between nodes,
+- runtime started or reused,
+- user or agent that started the workflow,
+- workflow run id,
+- parent workflow run id when nested,
+- errors and retries,
+- timing and status.
+
+The goal is maximum explainability:
+
+```text
+Runtime Tracing
++ Terminal View
++ Node Tracing
++ State Tracing
++ Transition Tracing
++ Dataflow Between Nodes
+```
+
+This allows users and agents to understand not only what a runtime did, but why the workflow made each decision.
+
+## 10. Framework And Dependency Principles
+
+Pibo should not make LangChain or any large framework a direct target dependency by default.
+
+The intended evaluation process is:
+
+```text
+Study LangGraph / LangChain and alternatives
+→ check licenses
+→ understand architecture principles
+→ decide whether direct use is allowed and useful
+→ otherwise create neutral cleanroom specs
+→ implement a lightweight Pibo-native workflow layer
+```
+
+Important constraints:
+
+- Do not copy external framework code into Pibo without explicit approval.
+- Do not assume a license permits all desired use.
+- Treat external systems as references until dependency and license review is complete.
+- Prefer a small Pibo-native implementation when it fits the product better.
+- Keep the implementation aligned with Pibo Sessions, Pi Coding Agent, PyHosted runtimes, and Pibo tracing.
+
+## 11. Cleanroom Guidance
+
+When direct use of an external framework is not appropriate:
+
+```text
+1. Analyze behavior, concepts, and requirements.
+2. Write neutral Pibo-owned specs.
+3. Derive implementation from the specs.
+4. Do not copy foreign source code.
+5. Build a lightweight Pibo-native version.
+```
+
+This guidance is not legal advice. License and legal review are required before using, copying, or deriving from third-party code.
+
+## 12. Requirements
+
+- **REQ-001**: Pibo MUST introduce Workflow as the central process logic abstraction.
+- **REQ-002**: Workflow state machines MUST live on Workflows, not directly on Rooms, Projects, Sessions, Agents, or Runtimes.
+- **REQ-003**: A Session MAY be associated with a Workflow run.
+- **REQ-004**: The minimal Workflow MUST preserve current simple personal chat/session behavior.
+- **REQ-005**: Complex Workflows MUST be able to model graph execution with nodes and edges.
+- **REQ-006**: Workflows MUST support usage modes: `session-only`, `agent-only`, and `session-and-agent`.
+- **REQ-007**: Agents SHOULD be able to start allowed Workflows through a generic workflow tool.
+- **REQ-008**: Workflow tracing MUST record node execution, state changes, transitions, dataflow, runtime starts, initiator identity, status, timing, errors, and retries.
+- **REQ-009**: Runtime tracing and terminal views MUST remain available and MUST be connected to Workflow traces where possible.
+- **REQ-010**: External workflow/state-machine frameworks MUST be evaluated before dependency adoption.
+- **REQ-011**: Pibo SHOULD prefer a lightweight Pibo-native Workflow implementation unless an external dependency clearly fits product, license, durability, type-safety, and tracing needs.
+
+## 13. Open Questions
+
+- What is the first persisted schema for Workflow definitions and Workflow runs?
+- Should Workflow definitions be plugin-registered, database-managed, or both?
+- How should Workflow versions be represented?
+- How much of the graph should be statically declared vs dynamically constructed at runtime?
+- What is the exact boundary between Pibo Workflow nodes and Pi Coding Agent runtime sessions?
+- How should nested Workflow calls appear in Chat Web traces?
+- Which Workflows should be agent-callable by default?
