+---
+title: Pibo Projects Area And Project Workflows
+version: 0.5
+date_created: 2026-05-05
+last_updated: 2026-05-07
+owner: Pibo
+status: draft
+tags: [product, web-chat, projects, workflows, sessions, state-machine, graph, docker, worktree]
+---
+
+# Introduction
+
+This specification defines the revised Projects concept for the Pibo Chat Web App under the new Workflow architecture.
+
+The key change is that **Sessions are no longer the primary process logic unit**. Sessions remain concrete interaction or runtime contexts, but **Workflows** become the central logic, state, graph, and execution unit.
+
+The new conceptual mapping is:
+
+```text
+Rooms = Projects or user-facing containers
+Personal Chat = Standard personal chat room
+Sessions = concrete interaction or run contexts inside a Workflow
+Workflow = actual logic, state, graph, and execution unit
+```
+
+This specification depends on `spec/projects/spec-architecture-workflow-engine.md` for the general Workflow architecture.
+
+## 1. Purpose & Scope
+
+The purpose of Projects is to provide a project-oriented workspace for workflow-driven coding and project work.
+
+In V1, Projects focus on a **Standard Project Workflow** for implementation work:
+
+```text
+Spec → Implementation → Execution → Test → Loop → User Feedback → System Update
+```
+
+In scope:
+
+- A top-level `Projects` area in the Chat Web App.
+- Projects as the project-context replacement for generic room language in project work.
+- Personal Chat as the default standard chat room outside project-specific work.
+- Sessions as interaction/run contexts inside Workflows.
+- Workflows as the state-machine, graph, runtime-model, and process-model unit.
+- A V1 Standard Project Workflow.
+- Automatic session worktree and Docker worker creation for execution-capable Project Sessions.
+- Clear distinction between main workflow sessions and child/subagent sessions.
+- Workflow-level tracing in addition to existing runtime/terminal tracing.
+- An extensible session/workflow type system so future workflows such as Research can have their own states and logic.
+
+Out of scope for V1:
+
+- Removing the existing Sessions UI immediately.
+- Implementing every future Workflow type.
+- Implementing Research Workflow as a first-class UI flow.
+- Full Git hosting integration.
+- Full CI/CD orchestration.
+- Legal approval or direct adoption of any third-party workflow framework.
+
+## 2. Definitions
+
+- **Project**: A user-facing project context backed by a project folder. It replaces generic Room language for coding/project work.
+- **Personal Chat**: The standard personal chat room for lightweight personal work and minimal chat workflows.
+- **Workflow**: The central process abstraction. It owns state machine, graph, runtime orchestration, dataflow, and workflow tracing.
+- **Workflow Run**: One execution instance of a Workflow.
+- **Session**: A concrete interaction or runtime context associated with a Workflow Run.
+- **Project Session**: A Session associated with a Project and a Workflow Run.
+- **Main Workflow Session**: The primary Session through which a user interacts with a Workflow Run.
+- **Sub-Session**: A child Session created by subagent or runtime spawning inside a Workflow Run. It supports delegated work but does not own the parent Workflow's state machine.
+- **Project Folder**: The local workspace/root path associated with a Project. It is the source folder for session worktrees.
+- **Session Workspace**: The isolated worktree and Docker compute worker assigned to one Session.
+- **Workflow Type**: A family of workflow logic, such as `minimal-chat`, `standard-project`, or a future `research` workflow.
+- **Standard Project Workflow**: The V1 project workflow for coding work such as features, changes, bugfixes, refactors, cleanup, or similar implementation tasks.
+- **Research Workflow**: A future workflow focused on information gathering, codebase analysis, comparison, investigation, and recommendations.
+
+## 3. Product Model
+
+### 3.1 Rooms Become Project Contexts
+
+For project work, the old room concept should be understood as Project context:
+
+```text
+Room → Project
+```
+
+A Project:
+
+- has a name,
+- has an owner scope,
+- is linked to a project folder,
+- contains Workflow Runs and their Sessions,
+- provides project context for worktrees, cleanup, specs, plans, and knowledge.
+
+The UI in the Projects area must use Project language, not Room language.
+
+### 3.2 Personal Chat Becomes The Default Standard Room
+
+The Personal Chat remains the default place for lightweight personal work.
+
+Under the Workflow architecture, Personal Chat should use a minimal Workflow:
+
+```text
+Personal Chat Session
+→ Minimal Workflow
+→ simple runtime run
+```
+
+This preserves current chat/session behavior while moving the product model toward Workflow-backed execution.
+
+### 3.3 Sessions Are Not The Primary Logic Unit
+
+A Session is no longer the place where process logic lives.
+
+A Session provides:
+
+- conversation or interaction surface,
+- runtime transcript context,
+- session hierarchy for subagents,
+- routing identity,
+- optional worktree/Docker worker association.
+
+A Workflow provides:
+
+- state machine,
+- graph nodes,
+- transitions,
+- orchestration,
+- dataflow,
+- retry and failure semantics,
+- workflow-level tracing.
+
+### 3.4 Everything With Process Logic Is A Workflow
+
+Project work must be modeled as Workflows.
+
+A Workflow is simultaneously:
+
+```text
+Workflow
+= State Machine
+= Graph
+= Runtime Model
+= Process Model
+= Extensible Execution Unit
+```
+
+The state machine lives on the Workflow, not on the Project, Room, Session, Agent, or Runtime.
+
+## 4. Workflow Types In Projects
+
+### 4.1 V1 Workflow Type: Standard Project Workflow
+
+V1 implements the `standard-project` Workflow type.
+
+It is used for:
+
+- features,
+- changes,
+- bugfixes,
+- refactors,
+- cleanup work,
+- similar coding tasks.
+
+It is the default Workflow for new Project work in V1.
+
+### 4.2 Future Workflow Type: Research Workflow
+
+A future `research` Workflow may support:
+
+- information gathering,
+- codebase analysis,
+- log analysis,
+- library/framework comparison,
+- design exploration,
+- tradeoff summaries,
+- recommendations.
+
+A Research Workflow may have different states from the Standard Project Workflow. Example future states:
+
+```text
+question -> research -> analysis -> summary -> completed
+```
+
+Research is intentionally not implemented in V1, but the architecture must not hard-code the Standard Project Workflow as the only possible workflow.
+
+### 4.3 Workflow Type Extensibility
+
+Each Workflow Type should be able to define:
+
+- state names,
+- state classes,
+- graph nodes,
+- allowed transitions,
+- default prompts,
+- runtime orchestration rules,
+- available UI actions,
+- completion semantics,
+- failure semantics,
+- tracing metadata.
+
+Adding a new Workflow Type must not require rewriting the Standard Project Workflow.
+
+## 5. Standard Project Workflow
+
+### 5.1 Flow
+
+The V1 Standard Project Workflow is:
+
+```text
+User Input
+→ Spec Creation or Spec Update
+→ Implementation
+→ Execution
+→ Test / Validation
+→ Error or Improvement Loop
+→ User Feedback
+→ System Update / Persistence
+```
+
+Short form:
+
+```text
+Spec → Implementation → Execution → Test → Loop → User Feedback → System Update
+```
+
+This supersedes the earlier idea that the state machine belongs to a Project Session. The Session is only the interaction/run context. The Workflow owns the state machine and graph.
+
+### 5.2 Standard Workflow Nodes / States
+
+The initial Standard Project Workflow should include these logical stages:
+
+- `spec`: Convert user intent or requested changes into durable specs.
+- `implementation`: Write or modify code according to the spec.
+- `execution`: Run the changed system or relevant commands.
+- `test`: Validate with typechecks, tests, builds, browser checks, or other configured checks.
+- `loop`: Decide whether failures or requested improvements require another implementation pass.
+- `user_feedback`: Hand ready work to the user for review and acceptance.
+- `system_update`: Persist accepted results, cleanup state, release workers, and update project/system records.
+- `completed`: The Workflow Run is finalized.
+- `failed`: The Workflow Run could not be completed within retry or safety limits.
+- `discarded`: The user or system intentionally abandons the Workflow Run.
+
+Implementation may represent some stages as states, graph nodes, or both. The product requirement is that the Workflow trace makes the flow visible.
+
+### 5.3 Loop And Retry Semantics
+
+The Standard Project Workflow must support bounded loops:
+
+```text
+implementation -> execution -> test -> loop -> implementation
+```
+
+Requirements:
+
+- The Workflow Run tracks retry count and max retries.
+- Test failure may route to `loop` and then back to `implementation` when retries remain.
+- The Workflow may transition to `failed` when retries are exhausted.
+- The Workflow may transition to `failed` when the agent determines the work cannot be completed safely or correctly.
+- Each failed iteration must produce a durable reason and summary.
+
+### 5.4 User Feedback And Cleanup
+
+When the Workflow reaches `user_feedback`, the user can:
+
+- approve,
+- request changes with a reason,
+- discard.
+
+Approval moves the Workflow toward `system_update` and cleanup.
+
+Cleanup/system update should help answer:
+
+- What changed in the relevant session worktrees?
+- Which changes should be kept?
+- Which changes should be reverted or discarded?
+- Are tests still passing?
+- Should this be committed, pushed, merged, or left as a worktree/branch?
+- Should Docker workers be released?
+- Should Workflow and Project records be updated?
+
+## 6. Sessions, Sub-Sessions, Worktrees, And Workers
+
+### 6.1 Main Workflow Session
+
+A Standard Project Workflow usually has a main user-facing Session.
+
+The main Session:
+
+- is the user's primary interaction surface for the Workflow Run,
+- is usually associated with one feature/change/bugfix work item,
+- carries runtime transcript and UI selection,
+- may have its own Session Workspace,
+- does not own the Workflow state machine.
+
+### 6.2 Sub-Sessions
+
+Sub-Sessions are created when the Workflow or an agent starts subagents or additional runtimes.
+
+A Sub-Session:
+
+- is a child Session in normal Pibo Session hierarchy,
+- receives a delegated task,
+- may have its own runtime and Session Workspace,
+- does not independently drive the parent Workflow state machine,
+- reports results back into the parent Workflow Run trace.
+
+### 6.3 Session Workspace Isolation
+
+Execution-capable Project Sessions must automatically create isolated workspaces:
+
+- A worktree is created for the Session.
+- A Docker compute worker is spawned for the Session.
+- The agent/runtime for that Session works only inside that Session's worktree and worker.
+- Browser checks, builds, tests, gateway restarts, and implementation commands run inside the worker context.
+- The host checkout must not be used as the experimental workspace.
+
+This is per Session, not per Project.
+
+## 7. Workflow Availability
+
+Project Workflows must eventually use the same usage model as the global Workflow system:
+
+```ts
+export type WorkflowUsage =
+  | "session-only"
+  | "agent-only"
+  | "session-and-agent";
+```
+
+Initial Standard Project Workflow usage should be `session-only` unless explicitly expanded.
+
+Future versions may allow agents to call allowed Project Workflows as tools, for example:
+
+```text
+call_workflow("standard-project", input, context)
+```
+
+## 8. Tracing Requirements
+
+Projects need both runtime tracing and Workflow tracing.
+
+Existing runtime/terminal tracing should continue to show individual Pi Coding Agent or PyHosted runtime activity.
+
+Workflow tracing must add:
+
+- Workflow Run creation,
+- node execution,
+- node input and output,
+- state before and after node execution,
+- transition decisions,
+- data passed between nodes,
+- runtime/session/worktree/worker started by a node,
+- user or agent that initiated the Workflow,
+- loop attempts and retry counts,
+- failures and reasons,
+- user feedback decisions,
+- system update and cleanup actions.
+
+The UI should let users understand both:
+
+```text
+What did each runtime do?
+Why did the Workflow move to the next step?
+```
+
+## 9. UI Requirements
+
+- **REQ-001**: The Chat Web App SHOULD expose Projects as the project-oriented area.
+- **REQ-002**: The Projects area MUST use Project language rather than Room language.
+- **REQ-003**: Personal Chat MUST remain available as the default standard chat room.
+- **REQ-004**: Project creation MUST require or resolve a project folder.
+- **REQ-005**: Project work MUST create or attach to a Workflow Run.
+- **REQ-006**: V1 MUST support the Standard Project Workflow.
+- **REQ-007**: The UI MUST show the active Workflow Type for a project work item when useful.
+- **REQ-008**: The UI MUST show Workflow state/progress from the Workflow Run, not from Session-local state.
+- **REQ-009**: The UI MUST distinguish main Workflow Sessions from Sub-Sessions.
+- **REQ-010**: The UI MUST show existing runtime/terminal traces.
+- **REQ-011**: The UI SHOULD add Workflow graph/state tracing as the Workflow system becomes available.
+- **REQ-012**: The UI SHOULD show Session Workspace metadata such as worktree path, worker status, web port, and CDP port when available.
+- **REQ-013**: The Standard Project Workflow feedback phase MUST expose approve, request-changes-with-reason, and discard actions.
+- **REQ-014**: Cleanup/system-update actions MUST require explicit user confirmation before destructive operations.
+
+## 10. Data Contract Draft
+
+```ts
+export type WorkflowUsage =
+  | "session-only"
+  | "agent-only"
+  | "session-and-agent";
+
+export type ProjectWorkflowType = "standard-project" | string;
+
+export type ProjectSessionRole = "main" | "sub";
+
+export type PiboProject = {
+  id: string;
+  ownerScope: string;
+  name: string;
+  description?: string;
+  projectFolder: string;
+  metadata?: Record<string, unknown>;
+  createdAt: string;
+  updatedAt: string;
+};
+
+export type WorkflowRun = {
+  id: string;
+  workflowType: ProjectWorkflowType;
+  usage: WorkflowUsage;
+  ownerScope: string;
+  projectId?: string;
+  state: string;
+  version?: string;
+  retryCount?: number;
+  maxRetries?: number;
+  metadata?: Record<string, unknown>;
+  createdAt: string;
+  updatedAt: string;
+};
+
+export type ProjectWorkflowSession = {
+  projectId: string;
+  workflowRunId: string;
+  piboSessionId: string;
+  role: ProjectSessionRole;
+  parentWorkflowSessionId?: string;
+  title?: string;
+  metadata?: Record<string, unknown>;
+  createdAt: string;
+  updatedAt: string;
+};
+
+export type ProjectSessionWorkspace = {
+  projectId: string;
+  workflowRunId?: string;
+  piboSessionId: string;
+  sourceProjectFolder: string;
+  worktreePath: string;
+  branchName?: string;
+  dockerWorkerId?: string;
+  webPort?: number;
+  cdpPort?: number;
+  status: "creating" | "ready" | "running" | "released" | "failed";
+  createdAt: string;
+  updatedAt: string;
+};
+
+export type WorkflowTraceEvent = {
+  id: string;
+  workflowRunId: string;
+  projectId?: string;
+  piboSessionId?: string;
+  actorId?: string;
+  type:
+    | "workflow.created"
+    | "workflow.node_started"
+    | "workflow.node_completed"
+    | "workflow.node_failed"
+    | "workflow.transition_taken"
+    | "workflow.state_changed"
+    | "workflow.runtime_started"
+    | "workflow.user_feedback"
+    | "workflow.cleanup_action"
+    | "workflow.completed"
+    | "workflow.failed"
+    | "workflow.discarded";
+  payload: Record<string, unknown>;
+  createdAt: string;
+};
+```
+
+Existing implementation may bridge this through `PiboSession.metadata` while the Workflow store is introduced, but new product language should use Workflow terms.
+
+## 11. Future Extensions
+
+- Research Workflow.
+- Documentation Workflow.
+- Incident Analysis Workflow.
+- Release Preparation Workflow.
+- Migration Planning Workflow.
+- Agent-callable Project Workflows.
+- Workflow versioning.
+- Workflow graph editor or inspector.
+- Workflow templates.
+- Durable resumable Workflow Runs.
+- PyHosted runtime orchestration nodes.
+- Organization-like multi-agent Workflow graphs.
+
+## 12. Open Questions
+
+- Should Projects replace Rooms globally, or only in the project-oriented UI?
+- How should existing Pibo Rooms migrate into Project/Personal Chat concepts?
+- What is the first persistent Workflow Run schema?
+- Should Standard Project Workflow initially be `session-only` or `session-and-agent`?
+- Which Workflow nodes should create new Sessions, workers, or PyHosted runtimes?
+- How should Sub-Session outputs feed back into Workflow node outputs?
+- Which cleanup/system-update actions should be in V1?
